Cryptographic model
- HPAN = HMAC-SHA256, 64-char lowercase hex.
- pan_ct = AES-256-GCM, 12-byte random IV via SecureRandom, IV
  prepended to ciphertext+GCM-tag, whole array Base64-encoded.
- HMAC key loaded once at startup from AWS Secrets Manager,
  held in memory for JVM lifetime, must be 32 bytes.
- DEK rotation interval is in DAYS, configured via
  ${dek_rotation_interval_days} — NOT hours. (The platform
  index document still says "6-hour DEK cache" and is wrong.)
- DEK envelope encryption: KMS CMK encrypts a service-generated
  DEK; only the KMS-wrapped DEK is persisted in
  wdp.data_enc_key; plaintext DEK held in memory.

Encrypt path
- Order: JWT → @Valid (pan numeric, 13–19 digits) → DEK
  freshness check → rotateDEK if stale (synchronous, blocks
  request thread) → HMAC.hashPAN → findByHpan idempotency
  check → either updateLastSeenAtByHpan (hit) or AES-GCM
  encrypt + INSERT (miss) → 200 with HPAN.
- pan_ct is NEVER returned to any caller.
- rotateDEK exception handling: KMS or DB failure swallowed,
  old DEK retained, processing continues.

Decrypt path
- Order: JWT → @Valid (hpan non-empty; reason field accepted
  but unused) → findByHpan → findById(dek_id) called TWICE
  (bug: isPresent() then get()) → kmsClient.decrypt() (called
  on every request — NO in-memory DEK cache on decrypt path)
  → AES-256-GCM decrypt → updateLastSeenAtByHpan
  (@Transactional) → 200 with cleartext PAN.
- Same HPAN may be decrypted unlimited times. No one-time-use,
  no rate limit, no consume-on-read.

Exception mapping
- PANEncryptionException → HTTP 404 (semantic error — crypto
  failure mapped to NOT_FOUND).
- PANDecryptionException → HTTP 404 (covers HPAN-not-found,
  DEK-not-found, KMS failure, AES failure — indistinguishable).
- Other RuntimeException / DB exception → HTTP 500.
- @ToString(exclude="pan") on decrypt response.

